    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "An email message about a trip from Cape to Cairo in 1953, quickly followed up by a phone call was my initial introduction to the Lydia Luhman Pederson Collection. There was mention of eight large reels of film documenting rituals and traditions and travel from Cape Town to Cairo with an invitation to visit Rockford, Illinois to look at the collection. Conversation continued as Sonjia Olstad told me about her Aunt Lydia."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "On arrival at this picturesque farm, previously owned by Lydia, Sonjia and her husband, Jim, were keen to share the scrapbook they had forgotten to mention in earlier conversations. Bound in real zebra skin, its first page was an original hand drawn portrait of an African man with a feather in his hair. Further pages revealed typical postcards of the period, scenic photographs and letters from her niece. What immediately stood out was the center of the scrapbook. Chocked full of itineraries, menus, receipts and letters on introduction, it became clear that this could be a window, a personal account of private travel in Africa in the 1950s."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "A walk through the bedrooms upstairs revealed a bow and arrows attached to the wall, Dutch/ African wax print fabric and quilted panels of the pyramids, camels and pharaohs of Egypt. Within the barn were boxes of items carved in wood and ivory, beaded necklaces and sashes. Many of these items had price tags on them. In addition, there were items made in leopard skin; handbags, a collar, muff and hats. As we moved from one location on the next farm to the next, more materials from this trip were uncovered. We finally ended up in the sunroom where the reel-to-reel film were soon packed into the car with all the other items. It had become apparent that this collection was a rich source for research."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Sonjia and Jim Olstad were inspired by Lydia’s travels, and when an opportunity presented itself early in their marriage to go to Nigeria and work with agricultural cattle farms they couldn’t resist. Their three-year stay in Nigeria was cut short due to the outbreak of the Biafran war in 1967. The three calabashes in this collection are just a few items from their time in Nigeria that are also included in this collection."
    }), "\n", _jsx("strong", {
      children: "By Esmeralda Kale, George and Mary LeCron Foster Curator of the Herskovits library "
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.h2, {
      children: "Arianna Ray"
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "While working on this project, I have often thought of Frantz Fanon’s Black Skin, White Masks, published in 1952 only one year before Lydia took her voyage to Africa. In this famous work, the Martinician author recounts a moment in which a White child on a street spots him, points at him, declares to her mother, “Look! A Negro!”, and then - “I’m scared.” Fanon dissects the psychic impact of this moment of being racialized from the outside and made “other” within his own body as he is forced to see himself through another’s eyes."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "For the many months I have been researching the collection, I have seen the Africa of 1953 through Lydia’s eyes and I feel, in some ways, that I have grown to know her. She was enamored by the idea of Africa’s mystery. She seemingly blinded herself willingly to what didn’t fit her vision, openly acknowledging that the Africa of cities and modernization is not the true Africa to her. She got tired as her long trip went on, her notes and purchases slowly petering off as she worked her way up to Egypt. She was independent, going on this trip alone without her husband in the 1950s. She was creative and generous, wanting to share her experiences with the people back home who would never have the same opportunity. Lydia left us her Africa in her letters, notes, works of art, and receipts that she collected along the way. Flipping through her scrapbook is both fascinating and charming, permeated with 1950s graphic design and fascinating peeks into the logistics and costs of travel."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Yet she did not record the information that I have desperately wanted to know. Tasked with selecting objects to write about, I had to first determine where they may have been made and by who. I combed through thousands of pages of museum databases in search of comparatives that could give me a hint as to their origin. I looked in books and catalogues and online auction listings. I did my best to narrow it down, but often my identification must remain unproven. Tourist art of this ilk has not traditionally been valued by museums and, without going to Africa myself, I am left with the research I have been able to assemble, hopeful that it is helpful or interesting in some way to those who stumble upon this project. My sincere hope is that more expert eyes than my own can clarify the questions of origin and artist that I am unable to deduce."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Lydia did not record the makers of the objects she collected and perhaps was not interested in their facture; she seems to have bought several of her pieces from curio shops or other stores who did the sourcing for her. The interest for her like many other Western tourists was likely their perceived exoticism, their prototypical “Africanness.” Much as I yearn to know the artists behind the many beautiful objects she assembled, I have been forced to come to terms with the fact that I will likely never know. And so I asked myself, how do I value African makers without only seeing them through Lydia’s eyes? This is what led to our exploration of contemporary African artists whose work resonates with Lydia’s journey and the objects she collected. It is an imperfect solution but one that I hope brings balance to the fraught politics of White tourism that Lydia’s journey emblematizes here."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Throughout this process, I have learned an enormous amount. I have learned about mid-century African art, about the impact of tourism on local economies, about styles of South African beadwork, about the weight of camera equipment in the 50s, about innumerable extraordinary contemporary artists, and about the enriching process of collaboration. Discussions with Basia Kapolka, and Yian Wang were edifying, productive, and stimulating. As we worked through the thorny conceptualization of the project, the practicalities of executing our ideas, and the bumps that cropped up along the way, I was reminded of the importance of community to creation. The African artists who made many of the works we display here also likely worked in community, learning from their elders, exchanging ideas, and selling their wares alongside one another. It has been a privilege to be in community with Basia, Yian, and our many other collaborators and contributors and to see Africa from within but also beyond Lydia’s eyes."
    }), "\n", _jsx("strong", {
      children: "By Arianna Ray "
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.h2, {
      children: "Web Developer"
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Reflecting on the entire experience of developing the \"An American's Africa\" website, building the interactive map, and curating the content for our digital exhibit, I can honestly say it has been one of the most enriching and memorable parts of my master's journey. I’ll never forget the moment when Basia, Arianna, and I first came together in the main library, getting to know each other and learning about Lydia’s trip and the collection of objects she had gathered. From that point, we began building the entire platform from scratch, which was both a challenge and an exciting creative endeavor."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Working closely with the ArcGIS and development teams to explore different options for the website and interactive map was an invaluable experience. We also met with Esmeralda, who gave us deeper insights into Lydia’s collection, showing us the objects and scrapbook from her travels. After several months of collaboration and effort, we were able to bring together a digital exhibit that showcases selected mementos, along with 3D models, essays from researchers, interactive maps, and additional resources for visitors to explore."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "The final result is an interactive platform that allows users to engage with Lydia's journey through the 1950s, exploring the countries she visited, and learning about the contemporary artists from those regions. The \"An American's Africa\" website aims to provide a unique perspective on the culture, history, and society of Africa during this pivotal time, and it's been designed thoughtfully to encourage visitors to reflect more deeply on these topics."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "When I first joined this project, my understanding of Africa—especially during the 1950s—was quite limited. I knew that many countries were under colonial rule at the time and that Africa was often seen as a destination for sightseeing. But through my involvement in this project and my exploration of the history and culture of the people from that period, I’ve gained a much richer understanding of the challenges they faced and the resilience with which they overcame them."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "The 1950s were indeed a critical time in Africa’s history, as many nations were starting to move toward independence from colonial powers. While many countries were still under colonial rule, the drive for independence was intensifying. Culturally, African nations were wrestling with the legacies of colonialism—imposed European languages, education systems, and governance structures. Yet, despite these struggles, the 1950s also saw a cultural renaissance: African art, music, and literature began to thrive, signaling a creative and intellectual awakening."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "One of the most thought-provoking discussions we had was with Basia, Arianna, and Esmeralda about Africa's journey to independence. We all came to the conversation with different perspectives, and it led me to reflect on how complex the process of decolonization was. I had initially read that many countries gained independence peacefully, but Esmeralda, with her deeper understanding of the history, challenged me by asking, \"Which country?\" That question made me realize how nuanced the reality of independence was—many countries faced great struggles, and the process was far from peaceful in most cases."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "This exchange, along with many others during our work on the project, has been both engaging and introspective. It’s deepened my appreciation for the diversity of experiences across Africa and given me a broader understanding of its complex history. I also reflected on my previous work experience, where I had designed and implemented websites for commercial purposes. Those projects, while valuable, never focused on the stories and lives of real people. This project allowed me to shift that focus, using my skills to create something that speaks to the lived experiences and legacies of individuals. I’m grateful for the opportunity to contribute to something so meaningful and to be part of a team that worked collaboratively to bring this project to life."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "I am especially thankful to Basia, Arianna, and all the contributors for their creativity, support, and the journey we shared together. This experience has shaped my thinking in ways I couldn’t have anticipated, and I’ll carry these lessons with me long after the project ends."
    }), "\n", _jsx("strong", {
